// ============================================================================
// Example: Equivalence Chains with Justifications
// ============================================================================
// Demonstrates:
//   - EQUIV: blocks for step-by-step equational reasoning
//   - Justifications in square brackets [reason]
//   - Common logical laws (commutative, De Morgan, distributive)
//   - Definition-based transformations
//
// Features:
//   - Each step shows equivalence (<=>)
//   - Justifications rendered flush-right
//   - Multiple transformations in sequence
//   - Optional justifications (can be omitted)
//
// Common justifications:
//   - [commutative], [De Morgan], [distributive]
//   - [definition], [parentheses], [idempotent]
//
// See: docs/USER_GUIDE.md - Section "Propositional Logic" > "Equivalence Chains"
// ============================================================================

=== Equivalence Chains ===

** Solution 1 **

(a) Commutative property

EQUIV:
p and q
q and p [commutative]

(b) De Morgan law

EQUIV:
not (p and q)
(not p) or (not q) [De Morgan]
not p or not q [parentheses]

** Solution 2 **

(a) Definition of implication

EQUIV:
p => q
not p or q [definition]

(b) Multiple equivalence steps

EQUIV:
(p and q) or (p and r)
p and (q or r) [distributive]
(q or r) and p [commutative]
p and (r or q) [commutative]

** Solution 3 **

(a) Equivalence chain without justifications

EQUIV:
p or p
p

(b) Mixed justifications

EQUIV:
p <=> q
(p => q) and (q => p) [definition]
(not p or q) and (not q or p)
